{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539786"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:46:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16702"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16702"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.06,0.04,0.07,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94977"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77966"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4212"},{"type":"tags","id":"4383"},{"type":"tags","id":"4824"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32606"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43640"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94977"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of increased vaginal discharge and post-coital bleeding. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill which she intermittently forgets. She reports having two new sexual partners in the past six months and inconsistent condom use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Speculum examination reveals a mucopurulent cervical discharge with contact bleeding. A first-void urine nucleic acid amplification test is positive for \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E and negative for \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. Her urine pregnancy test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Single dose azithromycin 1g","Metronidazole 400mg twice daily for 7 days","Amoxicillin 500mg three times daily for 7 days","Erythromycin 500mg four times daily for 7 days","Doxycycline 100mg twice daily for 7 days"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with cervicitis caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E, confirmed by nucleic acid amplification testing. The presence of mucopurulent discharge, post-coital bleeding, and contact bleeding on examination are characteristic findings. Importantly, she is also newly pregnant as indicated by her positive urine pregnancy test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle dose azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended first-line treatment for chlamydial infection in pregnancy. It has excellent compliance due to the single-dose regimen and has been shown to be safe in pregnancy. The patient should abstain from sexual intercourse for 7 days after treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in pregnancy due to the risk of dental staining and effects on foetal bone development. While it would be effective against chlamydia in non-pregnant patients, it cannot be used in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E has been used historically for treating chlamydial infections in pregnancy but is less effective than azithromycin and requires a longer course of treatment, which may affect compliance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-line option for treating chlamydia in pregnancy if azithromycin is contraindicated. However, its four-times-daily dosing and gastrointestinal side effects make it less desirable than azithromycin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is used to treat bacterial vaginosis and trichomoniasis. It would not be effective against chlamydial infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing treatment, partner notification and treatment for all sexual contacts within the previous 6 months is essential. In pregnancy, a test of cure should be performed 3-4 weeks after treatment. The patient should also be referred for antenatal care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Azithromycin 1g as a single dose is first-line treatment for uncomplicated chlamydial infection in pregnancy.","All sexual partners from the previous 6 months should be contacted and treated for chlamydia.","Test of cure is recommended at 3-4 weeks after treatment in pregnancy."],"references":["Australian STI Management Guidelines. Chlamydia [Internet]. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/chlamydia/","Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of Perinatal Infections [Internet]. Melbourne: Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG); 2022. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77966"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16702"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77966"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-26T19:46:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-17T11:05:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94977"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading"